'''Declan Mulholland''' ([[December]], [[1930s|1932]]&ndash;[[June 29]], [[1999]]) was a [[Wikipedia:Belfast|Belfast]]-born actor who played [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure|Jabba the Hutt]] in scenes cut from the [[1977]] release of [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']].

==Biography==
Declan Mulholland was born on [[December]], [[1930s|1932]] in [[Wikipedia:Belfast|Belfast]], [[Wikipedia:Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland]].<ref name="MulhollandBFI" /> He played [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure|Jabba the Hutt]] in scenes cut from the [[1977]] release of [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']].

In Mulholland's scenes as Jabba, Jabba is represented as a rotund [[Human]] dressed in a shaggy fur coat. [[George Lucas]] has stated his intention was to use an alien creature for Jabba, but the special effects technology of the time was not up to the task of replacing Mulholland. In [[1997]], the [[List of changes in Star Wars re-releases|Special Edition]] re-releases restored and altered the original scene to include a computer-generated portrayal of Jabba.

[[File:DeclanMulholland_as_Jabba.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A scene from 1977 recycled for use in the [[1997]] release of ''A New Hope'' by inserting a CGI Jabba over Mulholland]]
The likeness of Mulholland as Jabba has been re-used to represent other characters in the ''Star Wars'' universe. [[Pablo Hidalgo]] used Mulholland's appearance as the basis for [[Opun Mcgrrrr]] in his [[1996]] short story "[[Spare Parts (short story)|Spare Parts]]."<ref name="Spare Parts">{{Journal|11|Spare Parts (short story)}}</ref> The trading card set [[2013 Topps Star Wars Illustrated: A New Hope|2013 Topps ''Star Wars Illustrated'']] used Mulholland's image to represent Jabba's henchman [[Heater (henchman)|Heater]]; Heater had replaced Jabba in a version of Mulholland's original scene rewritten for the [[1981]] [[Star Wars (radio)|radio]] episode "[[The Han Solo Solution]]."<ref>[[2013 Topps Star Wars Illustrated: A New Hope|2013 Topps ''Star Wars'' Illustrated: ''A New Hope'']]</ref> In the [[2021]] comic issue [[Star Wars (2020) 16|''Star Wars'' 16]], an [[Unidentified Son-tuul Pride member (Jekara system)|unnamed member]] of the [[Son-tuul Pride]] syndicate was based on Mulholland.<ref name="Star Wars 16">[[Star Wars (2020) 16|''Star Wars'' (2020) 16]]</ref>

Although his most famous role was left on the cutting-room floor, Mulholland had a long and varied career as an actor, amassing over fifty credits in movies and on British television between 1962 and [[1997]].

Mulholland appeared alongside ''Star Wars'' actors [[Jack Purvis]] and [[Kenny Baker]] in the movie [[Wikipedia:Time Bandits|''Time Bandits'']]. In this movie, his costume is almost exactly the same as the costume he wore as "Jabba."

